705656f-a.text:
Mc Kibben Street, north side, west of White Street, showing in the foreground, a section of the building that at one time housed Williamsburg's first plate glass works.  The next building (taking up most of the block) was in 1869, H. Lawrence's Brick factory, later it became a cardboard factory and in 1912, the Manhattan Leather Works.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

705657f-a.text:
McKibben Street, at the N.E. corner of White Street, showing the P.H. Kalbfleisch Chemical Works.  (George White owned this site in 1855).

1922.
